{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17588294","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17588294"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T09:05:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T09:05:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15126"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15126","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15126"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.03,0.56,0.06,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7814"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85676"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7814"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15126"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69971"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8095"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19051"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19054"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85676","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/85676"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EComplicated urinary tract infections (UTIs) are infections that occur in the presence of structural or functional abnormalities of the genitourinary tract, or in hosts with underlying conditions that increase the risk of infection or treatment failure.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about complicated urinary tract infections is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Enterococcus species are the most common causative organisms","Infections only occur in immunocompromised patients","Urinary tract infections in men are typically considered complicated","Single-dose antibiotic therapy is the recommended treatment","Structural abnormalities of the urinary tract prevent infection"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E remains the most common cause of both uncomplicated and complicated urinary tract infections, though \u003Cstrong\u003EEnterococcus\u003C/strong\u003E species are also frequently isolated. It is incorrect that infections \u003Cstrong\u003Eonly occur in immunocompromised patients\u003C/strong\u003E as they can occur in any patient with anatomical or functional abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrinary tract infections in men are typically considered complicated\u003C/strong\u003E due to their anatomical differences including longer urethra and prostatic secretions that have antimicrobial properties. This means that when men do get UTIs, there is often an underlying abnormality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESingle-dose antibiotic therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is insufficient for complicated UTIs which typically require longer treatment courses. The statement that \u003Cstrong\u003Estructural abnormalities prevent infection\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - they actually increase the risk of infection. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Complicated urinary tract infections occur in patients with structural or functional urinary tract abnormalities","Common causes of complicated urinary tract infections include Escherichia coli, Pseudomonas aeruginosa, and Enterococcus species","Urinary tract infections in men are typically considered complicated due to anatomical di